<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1436,1430,1778]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,393,1430,1455]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" reason="1">Subgenus diagnosis.</emphasis>
Body length: 
<quantity box="[561,672,1430,1454]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" metricValueMax="1.1" metricValueMin="0.9" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" unit="mm" value="10.0" valueMax="11.0" valueMin="9.0">9–11 mm</quantity>
. Male frontal calli only slightly raised over the head and not very close to each other, frontal area clearly visible between them (
<figureCitation box="[841,963,1466,1490]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="16.[151,250,897,920]" captionTargetBox="[157,1421,297,866]" captionTargetId="figure-587@16.[151,1436,279,876]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 5. Male head, dorsal view: A, C. schreberi; B, C. scovitzi; C, C. vahli; D, C. adamovichiana; E, C. kunzei; F, C. schaefferi. Scale bar = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5286907" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5286907/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Fig. 5D–E</figureCitation>
). Male antennae strongly modified: antennomere I dorsally expanded to form a high and large keel, usually with a pointed and curved expansion on external side; II small and subcylindrical; III strongly enlarged and swollen, with a deep incision on external side; IV–V enlarged, flattened and very close to each other; VI subcylindrical with a pointed and curved expansion, starting apically on external side and directed backwards; VII–VIII slightly swollen and cup-like, VIII larger than VII; IX variously shaped, but always very swollen and enlarged. Male maxillary palpi distinctly modified: palpomere I usually small and slender; II enlarged, flattened and slightly curved; III enlarged and swollen; IV variously shaped. Male protibiae with a high dorsal keel, variously shaped and not directed outwards, as in the subgenus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kaszab" authorityYear="1951" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Cerocoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Metacerocoma">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Metacerocoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see below).
</paragraph>
